5</rating>
< Text>
I shop year round for Operation Christmas Child--A shoebox ministry through Samaritan's Purse for children in need.  Barbie, Ken, Hot Wheels, and Uno card games are some of the shoebox favorites.  When I arrived at the Mattel Toy Store, I was warmly greeted by Esperanza "Espie"--She helped me get started on my shopping spree.  She also told about the specials for the week and told me about the birthday club; I signed up my grandchildren...Can't wait to take them shopping during their birthday weeks!!  Out on the store floor, I was again warmly greeted by Susan who assisted me in finding other potential items that would fit in shoeboxes.  I made my way to the back of the store and found end cap shelves of green tag items discounted 50%!!  I found Barbie and Ken dolls and other miscellaneous items galore; the boxes were squashed but it certainly doesn't matter to me as I need to remove the packaging to properly fit them in the shoeboxes anyway.  Once I was ready to check out, Cynthia was very helpful and even watched the running total so I could stay within my budget.  She stamped my frequent buyer cards...WooHoo!!!  More savings!!!  The frequent buyer card earns you a star for every $10 dollars you spend, the card has ten stars; once you fill up the card, you get $10 dollars off your next purchase...Another way to save!!!  I would definitely recommend the Mattel Toy Store.  Thanks to the staff there, I really felt special shopping there!!!  I'll be back soon!!!</Text>

Food is good, especially the bread. Bread reminds me of San Francisco, as it should, that's what they do! < Text>
This is a reasonably priced spot for lunch or a light dinner. The people who work here are very friendly, which is a highlight for me, and the food is fine. I find it to be slightly lower priced and better quality than similar places like Panera or the Corner Bakery, though those places have better stuff for breakfast. That said, this is still a chain and their specialty is bread. So if you are satisfied with good, this is your place, but if you are looking for an amazing sandwich, you'll have to go elsewhere.< /Text>

This is a taste of home for any Northern California transplant. Get the avocado turkey sandwich, clam chowder in a bread bowl, a to-go little turtle for fun, oh and secret free stuff- kids can get a free little sourdough sardine to play with or gnaw on. Clean bathrooms. The decor reminds you of the San Francisco Bay area which is its hometown. Decent cookies and pastries. Lots of cute sourdough shapes. Bears, crocodiles, lobsters, turtles, fish, you can even ask for custom shapes if you give them enough heads up.</review>

<Text>Nice spot for a light meal. From my visits I have been satisfied with the portions served here. The sourdough breadbowls have always been a positive experience and satisfys the sourdough crave. In addition, the soups are fantastic.

Furthermore, Bodins is known for imitating different objects with their sourdough bread. If you want sourdough bread in the shape of a turtle, alogator, teddy bear, etc. Boudins can accomplish that. Really neat for a party!

What I like is that their portions will not give you a heavy feeling in your stomach. And if you are hungry you can always order more. <Rating>5</Rating>< Review>
About 4 months ago my Galaxy S3's power port stopped working, and after calling around to a few places that said they can't fix it since the power port is attached to the main board, I found this place where I was told they could fix it.

I got to watch as my phone was disassembled, and talked to Tim as he worked on my phone about random stuff ranging from what he was doing to why I got in to computer science.  It was really great getting to watch him work as he explained to me what he was doing and showed me where the problem on the old part was.  He fixed my problem on the spot in about an hour and I walked out the door with a perfectly working phone.

Last week my phone had a different problem and I came back to Tim since he did such a great job with my first problem.  After taking my phone apart and chatting for about an hour or so, he was able to partially but not completely fix my problem.  Since he wasn't able to fully solve my problem he didn't charge me, though I insisted on paying for his time and the partial fix he was able to provide.

If anyone is in San Diego and their phone breaks, I would definitely send them over to SD Cell Phone Repair.  He definitely knows his stuff and it's nice to be able to chat with him while he's working.< /Review>

< review>
Just came back from this place after being referred from another cell phone repair shop that is much, much closer to where I live. It was totally worth the trip; I cannot say enough good things about Tim, his friendliness, and his professionalism. He was able to quickly diagnose the problem that I had with the cell phone that I brought in (I couldn't get my new digitizer screen to work). After identifying the LCD connection as the problem (not the digitizer), he put in one of his own LCDs that happened to be laying around, and left it in, free of charge. He promptly fixed my phone back to "like-new" condition, all while teaching a nice old lady how to use a smartphone from scratch. Also while I was in his shop, Tim took a call from another guy who was trying to do-it-yourself repair his own phone, and answered many of his questions about the process. After doing some quick research on parts, he advised the guy that replacing his phone would overall be more cost-effective to him than repairing it due to the parts being expensive for that particular model. Tim's prices are extremely competitive, and I couldn't be happier with the service. A+ business, and A+ human being.< /review>

< Review>
I was referred to this gentleman who I found to be very knowledgeable and knows a lot about cell phone troubleshooting.  My samsung galaxy s3 was having problems when I tried to charge it and I had to jiggle the USB cord to get it right and start charging. TIM took  a quick peek under the microscope and quickly diagnosed the problem to be a couple of loose connection pins. I said that if he had to replace the whole USB power port to go ahead and do it and he was honest enough to tell me that a simple soldering job with fix it. In and out in 5 minutes. I am glad there are still people in this world who are honest and hard working. I had gone to the cricket store where I bought the phone and all they wanted me to do was to upgrade to the s4. Save your hard earned money and go to Tim so he can salvage your good ol reliable phone.  Thanks again Tim.</Review>

I have lived here for four years (2017 to 2020) and I have loved this community in every way. I have nothing to complain or point out about Crossroads, but only have praises. <Date>1627155477840</Date><Rating>2< /Rating><Text>Crossroads is a good society with great features. I like it overall and thus have been living here for three years. However, society is going downmarket, and I have seen the overall experience erode. The community is certainly above average, but I am giving two stars to give readers an idea of things where it falls short. Before you move in, please note the following things about this place
1. Security is only for show: don't get fooled by the security patrol, the camera, and the main gate locks. Overall the security here is for namesake. The only place there is a lock is the main gate i.e, where from you enter when you come here to visit the property. There are many functional access to each building that is always unlocked. so anyone can come and knock on your door. Every other day you will find a solicitor knocking on your door.  Please note that main gate lock will keep your instacart and doordash deliveries at bay, and you will have to come down to let them in.
2. Faulty fire alarms: expect the fire alarms to go off every other week. Expect the building fire alarms in the middle of the night or during your work meetings.
3. No guest parking: because there isn't any security enforcement, the parking here is a joke. Don't ever expect your visitors to find parking. Residents routinely use the guest parking. If you live here, you will know that residents use all the guest parking. There will be cars parked in guest spots straight for 3-4 months.

< review>
I was not asked to write this review.

My wife and I moved in 3 weeks ago and so far everything has been great. The apartments are very spacious, well-priced and I have not had one occurrence of noisy neighbors (which is uncommon is large complexes). In fact, I barely see anyone around the place which means most people are staying inside and keeping safe during COVID.

I had to submit a maintenance request on day 2 which was handled efficiently. The booking system for the fitness area and pools are easy to use.

Location is great. Nobel Park is a block away. Anything else you could possibly need is 10-15 mins drive away.

Parking seems safe and secure. Elevators work. The complex is always clean and tidy.

People in other reviews complaining about rent staying the same while amenities are closed are acting crazy. It's a pandemic and La Jolla Crossroads is doing what they can to protect residents. At the same time, they are also a business.< /review>

<Review>La Jolla Crossroads is the absolute worst. Do yourself a favor and stay away it's not worth it. They're a wolf in sheep's clothing. The amenities and the units themselves are nice but they don't make up for the headache that is La Jolla Crossroads. The staff is unhelpful and rude. They act so pompous everytime you want to ask a question or even pick up a package. When they need something from you they will harass you nonstop but when you need something from them it's like trying to pull teeth.

I've had my car broken into twice while living here. The entrance to the garage says they have cameras but in reality they don't. I asked the front office about this and they said they 'planned' to install cameras but never did. Sounds like false advertising to me, when I rented this place I thought they had good security in the garages. The elevators are constantly broke and so outdated, sometimes they will be down for days. The building fire alarm constantly goes off and you're forced to evacuate during odd hours of the night. Throughout the week there are very few days when there is actual peace and quiet so you can't have your windows open. Between the gardners, dump trucks, fighter jets, maintenance, and cleaning crew it is the noisiest apartment I've lived in.

Due to COVID all of the amenities have been closed for months. Part of our rent is for using and maintaing these amenities but do you think they partially refunded our rent since they were all closed? Hell no. That probably never even occured to them, this place is owned by investors and they only care about one thing, $$$$$. I'm not the only one, just look at the other reviews. This apartment appears to be one of the nicest in UTC/La Jolla but has the worst ratings, that should be a red flag to anyone.

They have an excuse for everything and if you complain you're basically fighting a losing battle because they're part of GardenCommunities a huge real estate conglomerate. < text>
The complex isn't too bad as a whole in our building.  The apartment could use some updates in appliances as they are a bit on the older side.

I'll echo what previous posters have said in the fact that the walls are thin.  We can hear every step our upstairs neighbors make.  We also hear every door being slammed in the hallway.  We live near the trash room and are constantly hearing that door slam.  This complex is largely catered to college kids and some families.

The amenities here are nice and you get access to the 360 ones as well, like their bowling alley and basketball court.  They have lots of events each month as well.

We put in multiple service requests for our toilet to be fixed because the seat kept sliding and it took four times before they finally just replaced the bolt as opposed to tightening the old one that was stripped.

The parking garage is also an issue.  There are mirrors at the top as you come around some corners, however, the corners are just that, as opposed to rounded so you have to take it a bit wider which is hard when there are other cars.  The parking spots are also like most in San Diego and skinny in nature.< /text>

<Pics>None< /Pics><Text>Lots of pros and cons at LJX but overall I've been happy in the 11 months living here. We live in building 9155 which is a pet friendly building that I love except one annoying dog that never shuts up despite complaints. Overall the complex is quiet with the exception of screaming children at the pools or playgrounds on the weekends. The entire complex is extremely pet friendly and you will always see dogs being walked in the area, but the grounds are always clean. Most people do a good job of cleaning up after their pets and if not the landscaping team must. I always see cleaning crew sweeping the sidewalks and taking out trash so it looks well kept. The pools and gym are upscale and well kept. we get access to the 360 complex gym and basketball court which is gorgeous. You need a key to get through gates and a fob to get into Garages, so I've never seen an issue with break ins and I feel safe. These are the largest apartments you'll see in the UTC area which I feel justifies the high rent. Washer dryer In unit and huge living space and underground parking.

Guest spots are hard to snag and unfortunately there's no street parking nearby so friends have to walk from Renaissance Ave. The finishes are underwhelming and our floors are carpeted so that's a con.  we have a North facing balcony so the apartment is dark and patio never gets sun.

I will say the leasing office is slow to complete anything and hard to reach, but luckily I haven't had any major issues. Maintenance is awesome though! They come and fix things quickly.

Update: Rent did not get raised much at all. We moved to a different unit that faces east which gets much more natural light. Building 9135 is a bit louder since it overlooks the main courtyard. Overall still happy here!< /Text>< gmapID>

<Name>David Kruidhof<//Name><Response>{'time': 1389905521097, 'text': 'Thank you for your review.  We value your tenancy and are happy that you have called La Jolla Crossroads for 3 years.  We hope that all your future experiences at our onsite office are all pleasant.'}<//Response>< rate>

< text>
I lived at La Jolla Crossroads for three years now. The apartment itself is spacious and at a price that is about average or maybe a bit below average for the area. The management in the leasing office is hard to deal with as others have mentioned, although there are a few who actually seem to care and are helpful. I believe Lauren was the best.

Maintenance is awesome, you just have to put in a request online and give them permission to enter your unit and they get it done the next day. If you ask them to call you to make an appointment, you can wait a long time to never to get that call, so just give them permission.

The complex looks really great at first glance, but after you move in you quickly realize that this isn't really a great place. The appliances are low end, just like Costa Verde and La Regencia (same developers) and the outlets are still upside. The outlets make me wonder what else is going on behind the walls that was done with poor workmanship.

Security is a serious problem with this place. The door to our apartment doesn't have a peep hole or a chain, so you can't get any sort of preview of who is on the other side without opening the door. My wife's car was broken into ('97 Accord) and she had nothing valuable in view. They took her change container because there was nothing else in there worth taking. So no, having nothing valuable visible doesn't help.<//text>

I said, well, I might move then, because otherwise I'll have to pay the "month-to-month" rate for 2 months, which is an insane waste of money. <rating>1<//rating>< text>
RENTERS BEWARE, THESE PEOPLE WILL STEAL YOUR DEPOSIT ILLEGALLY ON WEAR AND TEAR ITEMS. Read carefully,
California does not hold the renter responsible for replacing things like carpet due to wear and tear. Think about it, you are a renter and you are paying to use that carpet. An owner is responsible for this, BY LAW. When you call them and try to dispute this, they say, "our carpets have a life expectancy of 5 years." Legally, that is the responsibility of the manufacturing company and they need to take that up with them. What does the warranty of the carpet have to do with you? This is their scam to collect your hard earned deposit money. I have lived their for 2 years and this is the type of treatment you get when you leave.

HERE'S WHAT YOU CAN DO ABOUT IT.

Go to google, search for Small Claims Court Form SC100 -
this is an extremely simple form even a baby can fill out. File suite against them in small claims...The address is listed on the forms. Make sure you put an extra empty envelope with a stamp and your return address because small claims court requires a "send back" envelope. Also a check for 50 dollar made out to City Clerk.  If you need any help at all, don't hesitate to call the small claims advisory service which you can look up on google. THEY ARE FREE AND THEY WILL TELL YOU EXACTLY WHAT TO DO. it is very easy to file a case in small claims and you shouldn't be intimidated at all. DEFEND YOUR RIGHTS! DONT BE LAZY ABOUT IT.< /text>

There are also a lot of cockroaches in the kitchen area. I tried to call maintenance about it, but they never did anything. So, I took care of it myself by using insect killing powders and traps. I ignored it because I already handled the issue 6 months ago. So, they send another one by coming into my apartment and sticking it on my fridge. Long story short, there are cockroaches everywhere, and they take 6 months to get back to you about getting rid of them.

There was also a mass shooting here right in the pool area. Yet, the only thing the staff care about is making sure they get new people to rent the apartments that people vacated after the shooting.

If you value being treated with dignity, safety, or at least not getting shot while going for a swim, do not live here! It is not safe for families!<//review>

< text>
Pros: Location (walking distance to shops, library, and malls)
Cons: Roaches + Unprofessional Staff

I have better things to do with my day than dealing with infestations or writing novels disguised as reviews - but here we are. If you'd like a slightly snarky take on the deets - ye shall read on...

ROACHES:
As soon as we moved in there was a roach infestation in our unit - presumably from the previous tenants.  As you can imagine I could immediately tell fun times were ahead.

When we made the maintenance request for the roaches and spoke to your maintenance crew over the phone,  maintenance confirmed that several other units at La Jolla Crossroads had roaches at that time.  My husband asked how this could happen and they said it was a normal occurrence due to units being empty and roaches go searching for food.

I was killing 4-10 roaches per day, during the day for OVER A MONTH -. It took a over a week for them to get to our unit and do the first treatment.  After the second treatment a week later it took a couple more weeks before I wasn't seeing roaches or new roach feces in my kitchen cabinets and drawers.

"Because nothing says yum like roach feces on your eating utensils."
-Said no one.  Ever.

We did not have a sanitary kitchen for OVER A MONTH (Nov 14- Dec 14). Yes, the unit currently is okay and I am happy about that.  There is no way there were no roaches prior to us moving in. After filling out 7 work orders your own maintenance guy said all the things that needed fixing should have been done prior to our move in - your third party vendors did not spend a lot of time in the unit.  I live in the unit 24/7 and while I only saw roaches a couple times a day (a few at time). I can easily see how your third party vendors could look over that if they are only in here for a couple hours at a time, especially when they looked over so many other things that should have been fixed prior to us moving in. This is coming directly from the mouths of your own maintenance crew.

OFFICE STAFF INCIDENTS:
On Saturday 1.21.18 I came into the office to get a shuttle pass.  My husband came in first and told the front desk I would come back with the form signed.  As soon as I walked in one of your leasing agents was very polite and helpful - I think his name is Rex but I'm not sure. I told him I was here for the shuttle pass and gave him the form I had already filled out.  He brought me to the front desk and I was standing behind him when one of your receptionists saw my signed form and said "Oh, the pest control girl?" with a smirk and tone that wasn't appreciated.  Rex seemed confused. The other receptionist is taller and saw me standing behind your leasing agent, got very uncomfortable and said "No pass, not pest" to try and sweep under the rug what just happened.  The girl who made the very unprofessional remark (which is apparently my office nick name among you when I'm not around) then saw me, got very embarrassed and did not acknowledge me at all.  She immediately looked down, then sat down and stared down at her desk.  No apology, just a lot of unprofessional awkwardness.  The other girl gave me my pass and I left.  *sigh*

What occurred on Saturday was really hurtful and uncomfortable.  It was mean and just shows a real lack of empathy and professionalism towards your residents/clients concerns.

I'm not here to win a popularity contest with your staff, but I also don't want to feel like I'm living on the set of 'Mean Girls'.

The negative talk about residents in front of other residents or potential residents isn't an isolated incident.  I have witnessed other agents talking negatively about other residents in front of me and others.

OVERALL:
Some staff is at least nice to your face.  If you are lucky enough to not have issues with your apartment the location is good.  BUT there are other apartments next door so if location is the only thing really selling the place I'd go next door I were you.</text>

<userid>102636407745322783907< /userid><Name>Zoe McCracken< /Name><Time>1467766532955< /Time>< rate>
1</rate>
< review>
Renters beware! La Jolla Crossroads takes advantage of its customers with added fees and horrible services. I encourage all people considering La Jolla Crossroads to look else where.

Don't get me wrong, I liked the apartment building. I and 3 other UCSD students lived in a 2 bedroom, 2 bathroom loft and the unit was beautiful. Unfortunately, this doesn't make up for its extreme shortcomings. The issues I had with the place are...

Deposit: This is the first place I've lived in that actually charged the residents more than their deposit when they moved out! The complex charged us for a deep clean and carpet replacement. I understand the deep clean, as that's pretty standard. However, the carpet change was completely absurd. We lived there for little over a year, and the carpet was new when I got there, and we didn't leave any big stains, so what gives? According to the California government, "normal wear and tear to carpets, drapes and other furnishings cannot be charged against a tenant's security deposit." Yet, I see the apartment changes the carpets in most units when residents move out. Apparently, the average person at Crossroads does more than "normal wear and tear."

Maintenance: They say that maintenance will come within 72 hours, which is a joke. Why make a promise they can't uphold? This is incredibly inconvenient when you have a clogged toilet or sink. They also tend to leave a mess when they leave. Don't get me wrong, I'm grateful someone unclogged my sink. However, I would appreciate it if they didn't leave the contents that clogged my sink strewn across the kitchen floor.

Service: Some of the people in the leasing office are extremely nice, which is why I feel so bad writing poorly of them. However, they're overall inconsistent, and some of the employees can be incredibly rude. When I wanted to give my 30 day notice, I contacted the leasing office, and the employee working their at the time gave me detailed instructions which I followed exactly. When I gave the leasing office my 30 day notice, I ended up getting chastised by another employee for following bad instructions, and they threatened to fine me. If I followed bad instructions, perhaps it was the person who was working's fault, not mine? I was able to talk my way out of the fine, but that doesn't make up for the poor treatment I received.

I loved my time here, and thought the complex was beautiful. However, that doesn't compensate for how poorly I was treated. There are so many other great apartment buildings in the area, don't bother with La Jolla Crossroads.</review>

<Text>Dear potential renter,
Dont get too biased by the overly bad reviews posted here, and remember: happy tenants wont bother to comment here. Its only the frustrated ones (for whatever reason).
I usually dont post on forums like this one either, but I felt obliged to say that I had no bad experience when it comes to repair/maintenance of my unit and getting  my security deposit refunded (minus a minor fee for floor cleaning, which I didnt want to do myself). Of course, if you run down the place beyond recognition, you will have to pay, but other than that its not different to anywhere else.
I decided to move out after two years because I thought the rent (which increases every year) was not reflecting the unit quality any more. My unit was unrenovated when I moved in, with outdated kitchen appliances, and I suggest serious modernization before leasing it again. I also didnt like the sterile hotel atmosphere (the place is way too big), frequent fire alarms, constantly broken elevators (which sucks if you live on 5th floor), and an overall dirty impression on shared areas like parking garages and elevators. But if you can afford it, and be lucky enough to grab a top floor corner apartment with no or only one neighbor (what I had), it may be a decent-good deal. The fitness center is among the best you can get in the neighborhood.<//Text><user>102498959840592269268< /user>< pics>
None< /pics>

< review>
Been living here for 3 years
Pros:
- Space (its huge)
- Maintenance (very quick and responsive)
- great price for the area (one can negotiate the price)
- Gym(good programs and size, trainers, avoid rush hours 6pm to 8pm at the gym as its difficult to find a machine)

cons:
- Summit Security (feel insecure with them rather than secure
- doesn't look like a trust worthy security company)
- management - they treat residents like pests, esp. the managers (few exceptions though)
- gas and water bill are shared by the whole building and the bill spikes(doubles) few times a year without any reason (neither SDGE/ISTA or La Jolla crossroads management can explain).
- Thin floor walls(walking after 10pm causes loud noises for downstairs neighbor and someone from summit security will show up midnight suggesting not to walk in the night)
- very difficult to find parking space for guest. There are a lot of pros but for me cons are very difficult to live with. Hence, my rating. So, its up to you to live here.<//review>

The maintenance is great, super friendly and quick, efficient service. Maintenance deserves more than 5 stars.

Everything else about management though? I wish I could give no stars. I don't even know where to start. Half of my apartment moved out months ago (did all the necessary paperwork and went through all the steps, got confirmation of release and everything) and they're still saying everyone's on the lease. We've been off the property for months now and it's still not resolved. Clearly there's some serious issues with communication and record keeping because this isn't even the first time we've had to reach out to them post-moveout for this same problem (and each time, we get reassured by the leasing office that everything's been taken care of but then it's back to square one again). Leasing office also only answer calls when it's convenient on their part and corporate never responds, period.

Tha garage gates are almost always broken, and I'm not even sure if this counts as a downside because the little clicker keys they give you to access the gates don't work half of the time so it's actually convenient (albeit not exactly safe for your vehicles; there's been a few break-ins that took advantage of this) when the gates don't work. Fire alarms go off so regularly it's actually an anomaly if you make it 3 consecutive days without one going off at some point.

First Review ever I've ever done. I'm usually chill about most things, but this had to be done.

The Good:
Gym was nice, well when it was 6:30am when barely anyone is around.
Neighbors have funny WIFI SSIDs

The bad:
It might just be my luck, but every time I've walked into the leasing office 3:00pm - 4:00pm  there was no one at the front desk and I would have to wait around 10 min for a quick question.

In the gym, some dude would place a towel on a bench to save his spot while using a whole other machine. This happened way too often. Finally decided to just go at 6:30am or 3:00pm

From the perspective of living in building 9115:

Found dog poop in the hallway

Neighbors were/are loud

WiFi and cellular signal are terrible. You have competing WIFI signals and the walls are terrible for signal propogation. Might be the piping in the walls

They put more effort into towing cars away than anything else,
People speed through the garages (there is no sign indicating a speed limit)
Cars and trucks park in red-zones on the round-a-bout area in between building 9115 and the leasing office making it hard to drive around. This was especially the case when there would be ONE MASSIVE TRUCK rig leaving me thinking "how the hell... did this guy fit this thing in here?!"

Elevators break down about every 2-3 weeks ESPECIALLY the ones closest to Judicial Dr.

People smash up the elevator buttons and so when you press them, it may seem like they elevator may be out of service, but you'd have to apply  hella force on the buttons (go super sayian 3 overlayed with kio ken x100)

A so called "Gated Appartment" yet the garage gates were broken, elevator gates were broken, key fob sensors were broken for half the year so anyone was able to get in. "Security"...

People are too lazy to actually put their trash down the trash chute which made the hallway smell like something died and also attracted roaches (Felt bad for the cleaning staff)

Emergency exit signs were smashed up

Fire alarm had gone off several times over the year (probably someone trying to be the next Chef Gordan Ramsay )

It has luxury in the name, but felt ghetto while living there. 360 Degrees is way more luxury than crossroads. Casa Mira View is way nicer than crossroads, but those speed bumps though

The Ugly
And then there was that shooting in the swimming pool right next to my building... Now there is a child left without a mother. Sad.<//review>

<UserId.>106158989992985112182<//UserId.><user_name>Danielle Miller< /user_name><date>1452639857141</date><Rate>2</Rate><Review>Pros: good for the cost (it's low income housing, welcome to San Diego cost of living out of towners), good pools/grill areas, washing mchines in unit, despite a few maintentance issues maintenance came quickly and fixed everything or replaced what need to be replaced, cheap rent, good area (walking distance from the mall, a CVS, some good restaurants, a post office, running trail, library and large park, and a short drive or long walk to a few grocery stores, food places, and one of the best hospitals in the country).

Cons: floorplans were designed by the most unqualified, idiot architect - have fun with two doors not being able to be open at once, placing furniture, and other subtle slightly annoying nuances. Kitchen appliances are AWFUL, they nickel and dime you in a legal but not very ethical way on bills (our water, trash, everything but wifi and electric seem to be not metered per apartment, but divided equally among all units in the building? We were charged for water/etc in a month we were gone for the entire month/few months, and at the same amount as when we are home and using the water). The no pet rule isn't applied at all or too many people don't understand that calling your unbehaved pet a service animal when it's not is demeaning to those of us to have a service animal (I do. The way you tell is if they have their harness on saying they're a service animal when out and about - this is day one of their training and certification stuff) - it also means you don't know what level of fleas or hair might be in your apartment when you move in because they obviously don't clean the place before you move in (our place certainly wasn't).

however, it's a good place for what you're paying. I wouldn't mind living here another year if I didn't have to relocate cities.

EDIT: YIKES! since moving out I had to deal with getting the deposit back and apparently they screw everyone over. The apartment was impeccable, barely lived in. The walls were never painted and nothing was ever hung on them. There was zero carpet damage and I even had a professional come in beforehand just to be sure. It took 4 appointments for a maintenance guy to actually SHOW UP for the inspection, and he walked around said it looked immaculate and no repairs would be needed, and left. No paper was given for repairs (law in california unless nothing needs to be done), and then $340 was taken off our deposit for "wall painting" and "repairs." Not only that but it took them 35 days to get us our check - that's illegal in California. They didn't even send it out until the 28th. If a landlord doesn't have a check in your hands in 21 days (no excuses) they have to pay you double the deposit. I'm heading to small claims court this week over this bs - but I don't live in San Diego anymore so you can imagine the hassle. Before this I would've rated them 4stars, but with this edit I rate them 2 star.</Review>< Pics>

< text>
A co-worker invited me for lunch and I enjoyed this place. From the outside looks like a small place. They do provide parking in the rear. We entered through the rear up some stairs. Once inside we were greeted and given the choice to select our seats.

We sat down and we were given the menus(photo avail.). I asked for a Ensalada drink, two pupusas(revueltos with jalape√±o), and an order of chicharr√≥n (light fried). I enjoyed these menu items very much.

No pressure from the server to up and leave. I enjoyed myself very much. Will I return? Yes please!

Thank you.< /text>

<Review>One of the better places in LA to get pupusas.

Had the debate with my wife over street pupusas for 1.50 or molcajete for 3-3.50 per pupusa.

I told her 1.50 for an inconsistent flavors and a small sized pupusa with mediocre ingredients on the street and potentially have a " none enjoyable" dinner or go to this restaurant and have a somewhat premium Salvadorean pupusa that you will 100% enjoy at a slightly higher cost.

Guess what the answer was..

Oh and get Get large sides of condiments for the pupusas it goes a long way.

This place is generally consistent with their taste, the employees are very nice all the time and the restaurant is a nice place if you can find a seat during covid times.<//Review>< Pictures>

< text>
This was my first time coming here and I'm blown away by there customer service!! The food was delicious!! My mom ordered some popusas revueItas and I ordered vegan popusas with beans and vegan cheese and a hot chocolate with soy milk. I original accidentally ordered popusas revueltas with vegan cheese and beans thinking that was the name of the popusas that have vegan cheese and beans but the kind cashier informed me that those popusas had chicharon in them so it wasn't vegan. Even though it was my mistake for ordering them in the first place, the cashier was super kind and generous in making me another order of the correct vegan popusas without charging me. You can tell this business and their workers truly cares about customer service and satisfaction! Also their hot chocolate is heavenly!! I've never tasted hot chocolate that good in my life! It was so good I had to order another one for my mom and due to the previous mishap of me ordering the wrong popusas which again was completely my fault, the cashier's made me a second hot chocolate without charge. I can't stress enough how understanding and caring these restaurant workers are! Will definitely be coming more often whenever I'm nearby!<//text>

< Review>
Great service all the way from the start as we came in we were greeted and seated. The food was awesome and if you want true authentic Salvadorean food this is it. The popusa was the best I have tried to date and el Pulgarsito plate we ordered comes with a lil of everything and all was very good. We will definitely be coming back soon.< /Review>

<text>Today for lunch ,I had the taste for for those delicious Los Molcajetes pupusas ( by the way  at this location the best in town) But the music was so laud and out of tune with an El Salvadorean pupuseria . I requested to please lower the volume because I could not listen to my friends conversation. < user>
108514343709762008578<//user>
< Text>
This place has great Salvadorian food. I've ordered Pupusas here a few times and they're pretty tasty. The one thing about them is they make them to order, so expect your food to be ready in 40-45 minutes after you call. I have never dined in, just picked up takeout. My last order had bean and cheese pupusas, regular cheese, and  Carne Asasa fries, which were really robust and tasty!

If you have time to wait and want some good pupusas, I'd recommend. Parking is street parking and it's right on Temple so it can be busy, but if you're just grabbing food it's pretty simple.</Text>

< name>
Ayisha Gabri<//name>
<review>My wife and I have always been on the search for good and authentic Mexican food since we moved from California in 1978. This place serves authentic street food!
I had menudo and it was the best I have had outside of Mexico and the Southwest. I also had an outstanding cheese and jalapeno tamale. My wife had a chile relleno which is the best she has had in the East.
The chips are not as fresh as I would like  but the salsas are outstanding.
We ordered two burritos to go. Wow. The spicy pork is outstanding. The Chorizo is equally as good.
This is a classic hole in the wall restaurant. It is not a place for a first date but it is the kind of place where you know you will get good food. It is not fancy. The services is nice.
The prices are incredible when you look at the quality of the food.
I rank it on equal par with Rincon and Los Portales.
Los Molcajetes makes this ex-Californian very happy< /review><resp>None<//resp><Rate>4< /Rate>< Pics>
None</Pics>
</record></dataset><record>
